All Cicero’s philosophica] works are written in the form of dia- logum, but the dialogue was of the later Greek type, and not of the kind with which we are so familiar from the works of Plato. 'ihis form seems to have died with Plato. The later form was much less dra· matic, contained much less of question and answer and of repartee, and much more of continuous exposition. The conversation between the characters was confined to asew episodes, and the various conflicting views of the subject discussed were delivered in uninterrupted‚ or scarcely intermpted speeches oi considerable length⁸.
